      <odd id="aspace_cf655eb33eb3922bcc2308b0749bb189">
         <head>General note</head>
         <p>Forms part of Yale Record Group 2-A (YRG 2-A), Records of the President.</p>  
      </odd>
      <acqinfo id="aspace_ce40e436dd3e817ea838fd5079ecd8e0">
         <head>Immediate Source of Acquisition</head>
         <p>The records were transferred from the Office of the President, 1977 and 1980.</p>  
      </acqinfo>
      <accessrestrict id="aspace_8097b7cffeee53c5af18557fd645e8a9">
         <head>Conditions Governing Access</head>
         <p>The materials are open for research.</p>  
      </accessrestrict>
      <prefercite id="aspace_2852b6abd86e912c0c04f30a28ff13e2">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>Ivy Group Presidents Records (YRU 17). Manuscripts and Archives, Yale University Library.</p>  
      </prefercite>
      <arrangement id="aspace_bab0bce62cdf9df7ffdfc4f777ae643d">
         <head>Arrangement</head>
         <p>The records are arranged alphabetically by subject.</p>  
      </arrangement>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_d68eaaa5a858698527bc513df14aa00e">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The records include the original agreement establishing the group in 1954; meeting agendas, outlines, and background materials; comprehensive files on intercollegiate athletics; documents outlining policy discussions and decisions on academic scholarships and admissions; the Ivy Group charter and handbook, 1972; and materials on Yale University's dispute with the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) over the Jack Langer case. The Ivy Group Presidents formed in 1954 to foster amateurism in collegiate athletics. Soon after, the organization broadened its mission and began meeting regularly to discuss educational philosophy and to formulate policies governing Ivy League academics, athletics, admissions, and scholarships.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
